{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-05155/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-05155"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:51:55"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["plan américain"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["group shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A group of reporters take notes."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-05155","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-05155"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1/1ddae872-d550-4854-8505-9da557263b7b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:03:29.684Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>This shot allows us to feel the discomfort and intensity of the press conference. Two of the reporters in the front row are both smiling slightly, almost as if holding back laughter. The reporters are clearly not here in good faith—they are looking for a story, and to them Barbara is a spectacle, something to be mocked and questioned. The lights appear almost blindingly bright and obscure some of the reporters' faces. The shot is positioned so that we are in Barbara Rose’s position and see the crowd as she would. To her, this mass of semi-faceless, mocking reporters, and blinding lights must feel incredibly hostile and uncomfortable.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:19.298017537883965,36.28583021993446,279.9829209748891,244.80243722304286"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1/f1f366e7-089d-46e6-ad4a-942b92015314","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:04:10.754Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The reporter who asks what will happen to Barbara Rose’s property once she is married says that he is from the <em>Daily Mail</em>, a notoriously conservative tabloid known for publishing salacious, sometimes untrue, stories. His affiliation signals to the audience that the reporter is likely seeking to create drama with his question, or to uncover some scandal. His emphasis on her husband’s foreign status, asking if her holdings will become “Dominican property” speaks to the conservative leanings of the publication, and its specific anti-immigrant stance.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05155/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1413.2095758835264,389.4616056999938,288.1808530280648,499.5476366322009"}}}]}]}]}